span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Menstrual_fluid">Menstrual =
fluid</h3></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Menstrual_fluid_in_cup_2nd_day_40s_female.jpg=
" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/thumb/d/d0/Menstrual_fluid_in_cup_2nd_day_40s_female.jpg/25=
0px-Menstrual_fluid_in_cup_2nd_day_40s_female.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=
=3D"250" height=3D"228" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2218" =
data-file-height=3D"2022"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Menstrual_cup" title=3D"Menstrual cup">Menstrual cup</a> filled wit=
h menstrual fluid</figcaption></figure>
<p>The average volume of menstrual fluid during a monthly menstrual period =
is 35&nbsp;ml (1.2&nbsp;US&nbsp;fl&nbsp;oz) with 10=E2=80=9380&nbsp;ml (0.3=
4=E2=80=932.71&nbsp;US&nbsp;fl&nbsp;oz) considered typical. <i>Menstrual fl=
uid</i> is the correct term for the flow, although many people prefer to re=
fer to it as "menstrual blood". Menstrual fluid is reddish-brown, a slightl=
y darker color than venous blood.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Carlson_2004_14-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite=
_note-Carlson_2004-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span t=
itle=3D"Page / location: 381">:=E2=80=8A381=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>About half of menstrual fluid is blood. This blood contains sodium, =
calcium, phosphate, iron, and chloride, the extent of which depends on the =
woman. As well as blood, the fluid consists of cervical mucus, vaginal secr=
etions, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endometrium" title=3D"=
Endometrium">endometrial tissue</a>. Vaginal fluids in menses mainly contri=
bute water, common electrolytes, organ moieties, and at least 14 proteins, =
including glycoproteins.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-17"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Many women and girls notice <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Blood_clots" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Blood clots">blood clots</a> d=
uring menstruation. These appear as clumps of blood that may look like tiss=
ue. If there was a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miscarriage" ti=
tle=3D"Miscarriage">miscarriage</a> or a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Stillbirth" title=3D"Stillbirth">stillbirth</a>, examination under a=
 microscope can confirm if it was endometrial tissue or pregnancy tissue (<=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Products_of_conception" title=3D"Pr=
oducts of conception">products of conception</a>) that was shed.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
enstruation#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Sometimes menstrual clots or shed end=
ometrial tissue is incorrectly thought to indicate an early-term miscarriag=
e of an embryo. An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Enzyme" title=
=3D"Enzyme">enzyme</a> called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plas=
min" title=3D"Plasmin">plasmin</a> =E2=80=93 contained in the endometrium =
=E2=80=93 tends to inhibit the blood from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Blood_clotting" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Blood clotting">clot=
ting</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The amount of iron lost in menstrual fluid is relatively small for m=
ost women.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template noprint noexcerpt Template-=
Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Wikipedia:NOTRS" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wikipedia:NOTRS"><spa=
n title=3D"This claim needs references to better sources. (February 2021)">=
better&nbsp;source&nbsp;needed</span></a></i>]</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-20"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#=
cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> In one study, premenopausal women who exhibited s=
ymptoms of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron_deficiency_(medici=
ne)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Iron deficiency (medicine)">iron defici=
ency</a> were given <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endoscopy" tit=
le=3D"Endoscopy">endoscopies</a>. 86% of them actually had <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gastrointestinal_disease" title=3D"Gastrointestina=
l disease">gastrointestinal disease</a> and were at risk of being misdiagno=
sed simply because they were menstruating.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Temp=
late noprint Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research#Primary,_seconda=
ry_and_tertiary_sources" title=3D"Wikipedia:No original research"><span tit=
le=3D"This claim needs references to reliable secondary sources. (February =
2021)">non-primary source needed</span></a></i>]</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruatio=
n#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Heavy menstrual bleeding, occurring monthly, ca=
n result in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anemia" title=3D"Anemi=
a">anemia</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Hormonal_changes">Hormonal =
changes</h3></div>
<div class=3D"excerpt-block"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" hre=
f=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnot=
e navigation-not-searchable dablink excerpt-hat selfref">This section is an=
 excerpt from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_cycle" tit=
le=3D"Menstrual cycle">Menstrual cycle</a>.<span class=3D"mw-editsection-li=
ke plainlinks"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a class=3D"e=
xternal text" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DMenstrua=
l_cycle&amp;action=3Dedit">edit</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div><div class=3D"excerpt">
<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_cycle" title=
=3D"Menstrual cycle">menstrual cycle</a> is a series of natural changes in =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hormone" title=3D"Hormone">hormone=
</a> production and the structures of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Uterus" title=3D"Uterus">uterus</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Ovaries" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ovaries">ovaries</a> =
of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Female_reproductive_system"=
 title=3D"Female reproductive system">female reproductive system</a> that m=
akes <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pregnancy" title=3D"Pregnancy=
">pregnancy</a> possible. The ovarian cycle controls the production and rel=
ease of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Egg_cell" title=3D"Egg cel=
l">eggs</a> and the cyclic release of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Estrogen" title=3D"Estrogen">estrogen</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Progesterone" title=3D"Progesterone">progesterone</a>. The =
uterine cycle governs the preparation and maintenance of the lining of the =
uterus (womb) to receive an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Embryo=
" title=3D"Embryo">embryo</a>. These cycles are concurrent and coordinated,=
 normally last between 21 and 35 days, with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Median" title=3D"Median">median</a> length of 28 days. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menarche" title=3D"Menarche">Menarche</a>=
 (the onset of the first period) usually occurs around the age of 12 years;=
 menstrual cycles continue for about 30=E2=80=9345 years.
</p>
Naturally occurring hormones drive the cycles; the cyclical rise and fall o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Follicle_stimulating_hormone=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Follicle stimulating hormone">follicle sti=
mulating hormone</a> prompts the production and growth of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oocyte" title=3D"Oocyte">oocytes</a> (immature egg =
cells). The hormone estrogen stimulates the uterus lining (<a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endometrium" title=3D"Endometrium">endometrium</a>=
) to thicken to accommodate an embryo should <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Human_fertilization" title=3D"Human fertilization">fertilization=
</a> occur. The blood supply of the thickened lining provides <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nutrient" title=3D"Nutrient">nutrients</a> to a=
 successfully <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Implantation_(embryo=
logy)" title=3D"Implantation (embryology)">implanted</a> embryo. If implant=
ation does not occur, the lining breaks down and blood is released. Trigger=
ed by falling progesterone levels, menstruation (commonly referred to as a =
"period") is the cyclical shedding of the lining, and is a sign that pregna=
ncy has not occurred.</div></div>
