<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premenstrual_syndrome" title=3D=
"Premenstrual syndrome">Premenstrual syndrome</a> (PMS) is a disruptive set=
 of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emotion" title=3D"Emotion">emo=
tional</a> and physical <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symptom" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Symptom">symptoms</a> that regularly occur in=
 the one to two weeks before the start of each menstrual period.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1-3=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_:2_36-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-P=
remenstrual_syndrome_:2-36"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>36<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Symptoms resolve around the time <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_bleeding" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Menstrual bleeding">menstrual bleeding</a> begins.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1_35-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1-=
35"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Symptoms vary,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_Wom=
en2021_37-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
enstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2021-37"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> thoug=
h commonly include one or more physical, emotional, or behavioral symptoms,=
 that resolve with menses.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_Tiranin=
i_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstr=
uation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_Tiranini-38"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The range o=
f symptoms is wide, and most commonly are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Breast_tenderness" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Breast tenderness=
">breast tenderness</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bloating"=
 title=3D"Bloating">bloating</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Headache" title=3D"Headache">headache</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Mood_swing" title=3D"Mood swing">mood swings</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depression_(mood)" title=3D"Depression (mood)">dep=
ression</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anxiety" title=3D"Anx=
iety">anxiety</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anger" title=3D=
"Anger">anger</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irritabilit=
y" title=3D"Irritability">irritability</a>. To be diagnosed as PMS, rather =
than a normal discomfort of the menstrual cycle, these symptoms must interf=
ere with daily living, during two menstrual cycles of prospective recording=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_Tiranini_38-1" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenst=
rual_syndrome_Tiranini-38"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>38<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> PMS-related symptoms are often prese=
nt for about six days.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011_39-=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruatio=
n#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An individual's p=
attern of symptoms may change over time.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_sy=
ndrome_AFP2011_39-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011-39"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 PMS does not produce symptoms during <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Pregnancy" title=3D"Pregnancy">pregnancy</a> or following <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menopause" title=3D"Menopause">menopause</a>.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2014_40-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstru=
al_syndrome_Women2014-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Diagnosis requires a consistent pattern of emotional and physical sy=
mptoms occurring after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ovulation" =
title=3D"Ovulation">ovulation</a> and before menstruation to a degree that =
interferes with normal life.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP20=
03_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menst=
ruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2003-41"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Emotional s=
ymptoms must not be present during the initial part of the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_cycle" title=3D"Menstrual cycle">menstru=
al cycle</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2003_41-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_n=
ote-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2003-41"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A daily list of symptoms =
over a few months may help in diagnosis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_sy=
ndrome_AFP2011_39-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011-39"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Other disorders that cause similar symptoms need to be excluded before a d=
iagnosis is made.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011_39-3" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cit=
e_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The cause of PMS is unknown, but the underlying mechanism is believe=
d to involve changes in hormone levels during the course of the whole menst=
rual cycle.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2014_40-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_n=
ote-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2014-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Reducing salt, alcohol,=
 caffeine, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Psychological_stres=
s" title=3D"Psychological stress">stress</a>, along with increasing exercis=
e is typically all that is recommended for the management of mild symptoms.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2014_40-2" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenst=
rual_syndrome_Women2014-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Calcium" title=3D"Calcium">Calcium</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Vitamin_D" title=3D"Vitamin D">vitamin D</a> supplementation=
 may be useful in some.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011_39=
-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruati=
on#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Anti-inflammator=
y drugs such as ibuprofen or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Napro=
xen" title=3D"Naproxen">naproxen</a> may help with physical symptoms.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2014_40-3" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_s=
yndrome_Women2014-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In those with more significant symptoms, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Birth_control_pill" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Birth control pill">birth control pills</a> or the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diuretic" title=3D"Diuretic">diuretic</a>=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spironolactone" title=3D"Spironol=
actone">spironolactone</a> may be useful.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_s=
yndrome_Women2014_40-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2014-40"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011_39-5" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Preme=
nstrual_syndrome_AFP2011-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Over 90% of women report having some premenstrual symptoms, such as =
bloating, headaches, and moodiness.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrom=
e_Women2021_37-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2021-37"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Premenstrual symptoms generally do not cause substantial disruption, and o=
nly qualify as PMS in approximately 20% of pre-menopausal women.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1_35-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1-3=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antidepressant" tit=
le=3D"Antidepressant">Antidepressants</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Selective_serotonin_reuptake_inhibitor" title=3D"Selective s=
erotonin reuptake inhibitor">selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors</a> (S=
SRI) class may be used to treat the emotional symptoms of PMS.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1_35-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1-35"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premenstrual_dysphoric_disorder" t=
itle=3D"Premenstrual dysphoric disorder">Premenstrual dysphoric disorder</a=
> (PMDD) is a more severe condition that has greater psychological symptoms=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndrome_AFP2011_39-6" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstr=
ual_syndrome_AFP2011-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Premenstrual_syndro=
me_Women2014_40-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_Women2014-40"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 PMDD affects about 3% of women of child-bearing age.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Pr=
emenstrual_syndrome_:1_35-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Premenstrual_syndrome_:1-35"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up></div></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cramps">Cramps</h3></div>
<p>In most women, various physical changes are brought about by fluctuation=
s in hormone levels during the menstrual cycle. This includes muscle contra=
ctions of the uterus (menstrual cramping) that can precede or accompany men=
struation. Many women experience painful cramps, also known as <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysmenorrhea" title=3D"Dysmenorrhea">dysmenorr=
hea</a>, during menstruation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_prevalence_and_risk_fa=
ctors_of_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Menstruation#cite_note-The_prevalence_and_risk_factors_of-42"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Among adult women, 2%=E2=80=9328% have pain severe enough to affect daily =
activity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-The_prevalence_and_risk_factors_of_42-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_n=
ote-The_prevalence_and_risk_factors_of-42"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Severe symptoms that=
 disrupt daily activities and functioning may be diagnosed as <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Premenstrual_dysphoric_disorder" title=3D"Preme=
nstrual dysphoric disorder">premenstrual dysphoric disorder</a>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-WH2020_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-WH2020-43"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These symptoms can be=
 severe enough to affect a person's performance at work, school, and in eve=
ryday activities in a small percentage of women.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-AFP2011=
_9-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrua=
tion#cite_note-AFP2011-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>When severe pelvic pain and bleeding suddenly occur or worsen during=
 a cycle, this could be due to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ect=
opic_pregnancy" title=3D"Ectopic pregnancy">ectopic pregnancy</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miscarriage" title=3D"Miscarriage">spon=
taneous abortion</a>. This is checked by using a pregnancy test, ideally as=
 soon as unusual pain begins, because ectopic pregnancies can be life=E2=80=
=91threatening.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-44"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The most common treatment for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Menstrual_cramps" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Menstrual cramps">menst=
rual cramps</a> are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-steroidal_=
anti-inflammatory_drugs" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Non-steroidal anti-=
inflammatory drugs">non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs</a> (NSAIDs). NSA=
IDs can be used to reduce moderate to severe pain, and all appear similar.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhoea_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhoea-45"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> About 1 in 5 women do not respond to NSAIDs and require alternative ther=
apy, such as simple analgesics or heat pads.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_n=
ote-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup> Other medications for pain management include aspirin o=
r paracetamol and combined oral contraceptives. Although combined oral cont=
raceptives may be used, there is insufficient evidence for the efficacy of =
intrauterine progestogens.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhoea_45-1" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-=
Dysmenorrhoea-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>One review found tentative evidence that acupuncture may be useful, =
at least in the short term.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-47" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-47"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Another review found insufficient evidence to determine an effect.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Menstruation#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Interactions_with_other_con=
ditions">Interactions with other conditions</h3></div>
<p>Known interactions between the menstrual cycle and certain health condit=
ions include:
</p>
<ul><li>Some women with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neurology"=
 title=3D"Neurology">neurological conditions</a> experience increased activ=
ity of their conditions at about the same time during each menstrual cycle.=
 For example, drops in estrogen levels may trigger <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Migraines" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Migraines">migra=
ines</a>,<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"whit=
e-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Ide=
ntifying_reliable_sources_(medicine)" title=3D"Wikipedia:Identifying reliab=
le sources (medicine)"><span title=3D"Material near this tag needs referenc=
es to reliable medical sources. (February 2021)">medical citation needed</s=
pan></a></i>]</sup> <sup id=3D"cite_ref-49" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-49"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> especi=
ally when the woman who has migraines is also taking the birth control pill=
.</li>
<li>Many women with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epilepsy" titl=
e=3D"Epilepsy">epilepsy</a> have more seizures in a pattern linked to the m=
enstrual cycle; this is called "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ca=
tamenial_epilepsy" title=3D"Catamenial epilepsy">catamenial epilepsy</a>".<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-pmid18164632_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-pmid18164632-50"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Different patterns seem to exist (such as seizures coinciding with the tim=
e of menstruation, or coinciding with the time of ovulation), and the frequ=
ency with which they occur has not been firmly established.</li>
<li>Research indicates that women have a significantly higher likelihood of=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_cruciate_ligament" title=
=3D"Anterior cruciate ligament">anterior cruciate ligament</a> injuries in =
the pre-ovulatory stage, than post-ovulatory stage.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#c=
ite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Sexual_activity">Sexual act=
ivity</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Culture_and_m=
enstruation" title=3D"Culture and menstruation">Culture and menstruation</a=
></div>
<p>Sexual feelings and behaviors change during the menstrual cycle. Before =
and during ovulation, high levels of estrogen and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Androgen" title=3D"Androgen">androgens</a> result in women =
having a relatively increased interest in sexual activity, and relatively l=
ower interest directly prior to and during menstruation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-52" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruat=
ion#cite_note-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Unlike other mammals, women may show interest=
 in sexual activity across all days of the menstrual cycle, regardless of f=
ertility.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>There is no reliable scientific evidence that would advise against <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sexual_intercourse" title=3D"Sexual=
 intercourse">sexual intercourse</a> during menstruation based on medical g=
rounds.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-=
space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Ident=
ifying_reliable_sources_(medicine)" title=3D"Wikipedia:Identifying reliable=
 sources (medicine)"><span title=3D"Material near this tag needs references=
 to reliable medical sources. (February 2021)">medical citation needed</spa=
n></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Fertility_aspects">Fertilit=
y aspects</h3></div>
<p>Peak <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fertility" title=3D"Fertil=
ity">fertility</a> (the time with the highest likelihood of pregnancy resul=
ting from sexual intercourse) occurs during just a few days of the cycle: u=
sually two days before and two days after the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Ovulation" title=3D"Ovulation">ovulation</a> date.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-54" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Men=
struation#cite_note-54"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This corresponds to the second and the=
 beginning of the third week in a 28-day cycle. This <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Fertile_window" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fertile w=
indow">fertile window</a> varies from woman to woman, just as the ovulation=
 date often varies from cycle to cycle for the same woman.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstru=
ation#cite_note-55"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A variety of methods have been developed to=
 help individual women <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fertility_t=
esting" title=3D"Fertility testing">estimate the relatively fertile</a> and=
 the relatively infertile days in the cycle; these systems are called <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fertility_awareness" title=3D"Fertility=
 awareness">fertility awareness</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template T=
emplate-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Identifying_reliable_sources_(medicine)" title=3D"W=
ikipedia:Identifying reliable sources (medicine)"><span title=3D"Material n=
ear this tag needs references to reliable medical sources. (February 2021)"=
>medical citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Menstrual_disorders">Menstr=
ual disorders</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_disorder" =
title=3D"Menstrual disorder">Menstrual disorder</a></div>
<p>Infrequent or irregular ovulation is called <i>oligoovulation</i>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-56" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Menstruation#cite_note-56"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>56<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The absence of ovulation is call=
ed <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anovulation" title=3D"Anovul=
ation">anovulation</a></i>. Normal menstrual flow can occur without ovulati=
on preceding it: an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anovulatory_cy=
cle" title=3D"Anovulatory cycle">anovulatory cycle</a>. In some cycles, fol=
licular development may start but not be completed; nevertheless, estrogens=
 will be formed and stimulate the uterine lining. Anovulatory flow resultin=
g from a very thick endometrium caused by prolonged, continued high estroge=
n levels is called <i>estrogen breakthrough bleeding</i>. Anovulatory bleed=
ing triggered by a sudden drop in estrogen levels is called <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Withdrawal_bleeding" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Withdrawal bleeding">withdrawal bleeding</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-tcoyf3=
_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstru=
ation#cite_note-tcoyf3-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>57<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Anovulatory cycles commonly occur be=
fore <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menopause" title=3D"Menopause=
">menopause</a> (perimenopause) and in women with <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Polycystic_ovary_syndrome" title=3D"Polycystic ovary syndro=
me">polycystic ovary syndrome</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-emed2_58-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-=
emed2-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>58<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Very little flow (less than 10 ml) is called <i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypomenorrhea" title=3D"Hypomenorrhea">hypomenorrhea</=
a></i>. Regular cycles with intervals of 21 days or fewer are <i><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polymenorrhea" title=3D"Polymenorrhea">polym=
enorrhea</a></i>; frequent but <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irr=
egular_menstruation" title=3D"Irregular menstruation">irregular menstruatio=
n</a> is known as <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metrorrhagia"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Metrorrhagia">metrorrhagia</a></i>. Sudden =
heavy flows or amounts greater than 80 ml are termed <i><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menorrhagia" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Menorrhag=
ia">menorrhagia</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-emed1_59-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-emed1-59">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> Heavy menstruation that occurs frequently and irregularly is <i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menometrorrhagia" title=3D"Menome=
trorrhagia">menometrorrhagia</a></i>. The term for cycles with intervals ex=
ceeding 35 days is <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligomenorrh=
ea" title=3D"Oligomenorrhea">oligomenorrhea</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-afp=
_60-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstru=
ation#cite_note-afp-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>60<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Amenorrhea" title=3D"Amenorrhea">Amenorrhea</a> refers to more than thre=
e<sup id=3D"cite_ref-emed1_59-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-emed1-59"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>59<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> to six<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-afp_60-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-afp-60"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>60<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> months without menses=
 (while not being pregnant) during a woman's reproductive years. The term f=
or painful periods is <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysmenorr=
hea" title=3D"Dysmenorrhea">dysmenorrhea</a></i>.
</p><p>There is a wide spectrum of differences in how women experience mens=
truation. There are several ways that someone's <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Menstrual_cycle" title=3D"Menstrual cycle">menstrual cycle</a=
> can differ from the norm:
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable">

<tbody><tr>
<th>Term
</th>
<th>Meaning
</th></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oligomenorrhea" title=3D"Oligo=
menorrhea">Oligomenorrhea</a>
</td>
<td>Infrequent periods
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypomenorrhea" title=3D"Hypome=
norrhea">Hypomenorrhea</a>
</td>
<td>Short or light periods
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polymenorrhea" title=3D"Polyme=
norrhea">Polymenorrhea</a>
</td>
<td>Frequent periods (more frequently than every 21 days)
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypermenorrhea" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Hypermenorrhea">Hypermenorrhea</a>
</td>
<td>Heavy or long periods (soaking a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Sanitary_napkin" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sanitary napkin">sanitar=
y napkin</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tampon" title=3D"T=
ampon">tampon</a> every hour, menstruating longer than 7 days)
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysmenorrhea" title=3D"Dysmeno=
rrhea">Dysmenorrhea</a>
</td>
<td>Painful periods
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intermenstrual_bleeding" title=
=3D"Intermenstrual bleeding">Intermenstrual bleeding</a>
</td>
<td>Breakthrough bleeding (also called spotting)
</td></tr>
<tr>
<td><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amenorrhea" title=3D"Amenorrhe=
a">Amenorrhea</a>
</td>
<td>Absent periods
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>Extreme psychological stress can also result in periods stopping.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-61" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Menstruation#cite_note-61"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>61<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> More severe symptoms of anxiety o=
r depression may be signs of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Preme=
nstrual_dysphoric_disorder" title=3D"Premenstrual dysphoric disorder">preme=
nstrual dysphoric disorder</a> (PMDD) which is a depressive disorder.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-62" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Menstruation#cite_note-62"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>62<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysfunctional_uterine_bleed=
ing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dysfunctional uterine bleeding">Dysfunc=
tional uterine bleeding</a> is a hormonally caused bleeding abnormality. Dy=
sfunctional uterine bleeding typically occurs in premenopausal women who do=
 not ovulate normally (i.e. are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/An=
ovulatory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Anovulatory">anovulatory</a>). Al=
l these bleeding abnormalities need medical attention; they may indicate ho=
rmone imbalances, uterine fibroids, or other problems. As pregnant women ma=
y bleed, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pregnancy_test" title=
=3D"Pregnancy test">pregnancy test</a> forms part of the evaluation of abno=
rmal bleeding.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D=
"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedi=
a:Identifying_reliable_sources_(medicine)" title=3D"Wikipedia:Identifying r=
eliable sources (medicine)"><span title=3D"Material near this tag needs ref=
erences to reliable medical sources. (February 2021)">medical citation need=
ed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Women who had undergone <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fem=
ale_genital_mutilation" title=3D"Female genital mutilation">female genital =
mutilation</a> (particularly type III- <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Infibulation" title=3D"Infibulation">infibulation</a>) a practice comm=
on in parts of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Africa" title=3D"Af=
rica">Africa</a>, may experience menstrual problems, such as slow and painf=
ul menstruation, that is caused by the near-complete sealing off of the vag=
ina.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-63" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-63"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>63<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Dysmenorrhea">Dysmenorrhea<=
/h3></div>
<div class=3D"excerpt-block"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" hre=
f=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1066933788"><link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inlin=
e-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1320445320"><div role=3D"note" cla=
ss=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable dablink excerpt-hat selfref">This s=
ection is an excerpt from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysmenor=
rhea" title=3D"Dysmenorrhea">Dysmenorrhea</a>.<span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-like plainlinks"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a class=
=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDys=
menorrhea&amp;action=3Dedit">edit</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>]</span></span></div><div class=3D"excerpt">
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:MenstrualCycle_gen.svg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e=
/e7/MenstrualCycle_gen.svg/250px-MenstrualCycle_gen.svg.png" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"250" height=3D"313" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"800" data-file-height=3D"1000"></a><figcaption><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_cycle" title=3D"Menstrual cycle">Menstrual cycle=
</a> and changes in hormone production</figcaption></figure>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysmenorrhea" title=3D"Dysmenor=
rhea">Dysmenorrhea</a>, also known as period pain, painful periods or menst=
rual cramps, is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pain" title=3D"Pai=
n">pain</a> during menstruation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP21_64-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation=
#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP21-64"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrh=
ea_medline_65-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_medline-65"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>65<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2015_66-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2015-66"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> Its usual onset occurs around the time that menstruation begins.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014_67-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> Symptoms typically last less than three days.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014_67-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> The pain is usually in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pelvi=
s" title=3D"Pelvis">pelvis</a> or lower abdomen.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmeno=
rrhea_AFP2014_67-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Other sym=
ptoms may include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Back_pain" title=
=3D"Back pain">back pain</a>, diarrhea or nausea.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmen=
orrhea_AFP2014_67-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Dysmenorrhea can occur without an underlying problem.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Dysmenorrhea_Women2014_68-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_Women2014-68"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2018_69-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea=
_ACOG2018-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Underlying issues that can cause dysmenorrhea inc=
lude <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uterine_fibroids" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Uterine fibroids">uterine fibroids</a>, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenomyosis" title=3D"Adenomyosis">adenomyosis</a=
>, and most commonly, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Endometriosi=
s" title=3D"Endometriosis">endometriosis</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrh=
ea_Women2014_68-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_Women2014-68"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is mo=
re common among those with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menorrh=
agia" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Menorrhagia">heavy periods</a>, irregu=
lar periods, those whose periods started before twelve years of age and tho=
se who have a low body weight.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014_67-4=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation=
#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Pelvic_exam" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pelvic exam">pe=
lvic exam</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultrasound" titl=
e=3D"Ultrasound">ultrasound</a> in individuals who are sexually active may =
be useful for diagnosis.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014_67-5" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_=
note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Conditions that should be ruled o=
ut include <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ectopic_pregnancy" titl=
e=3D"Ectopic pregnancy">ectopic pregnancy</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Pelvic_inflammatory_disease" title=3D"Pelvic inflammatory dise=
ase">pelvic inflammatory disease</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Interstitial_cystitis" title=3D"Interstitial cystitis">interstitial cys=
titis</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chronic_pelvic_pain"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chronic pelvic pain">chronic pelvic pain</a=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014_67-6" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2=
014-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Dysmenorrhea occurs less often in those who exercise regularly and t=
hose who have children early in life.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP20=
14_67-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menst=
ruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-7=
0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruatio=
n#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> Treatment may include the use of a heating pad.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_Women2014_68-2" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_Wome=
n2014-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> Medications that may help include <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NSAIDs" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"NSAIDs">NSAIDs=
</a> such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ibuprofen" title=3D"I=
buprofen">ibuprofen</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hormonal_=
birth_control" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hormonal birth control">hormo=
nal birth control</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IUD_=
with_progestogen" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"IUD with progestogen">IUD =
with progestogen</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014_67-8" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_n=
ote-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_Wo=
men2014_68-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_Women2014-68"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Taking <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vitamin_B1" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Vitamin B1">vitamin B1</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Magnesium" title=3D"Magnesium">magnesium</a> may help.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-D=
ysmenorrhea_ACOG2015_66-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2015-66"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Evidence for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yoga" title=3D"Yoga"=
>yoga</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acupuncture" title=3D"A=
cupuncture">acupuncture</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ma=
ssage" title=3D"Massage">massage</a> is insufficient.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dy=
smenorrhea_AFP2014_67-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Surg=
ery may be useful if certain underlying problems are present.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2015_66-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2015-66"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p>
Estimates of the percentage of female <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Adolescent" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Adolescent">adolescents</a> =
and women of reproductive age affected are between 50% and 90%,<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_AFP21_64-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP21-64"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>64<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2018_69-1" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG=
2018-69"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">]</span></a></sup> and the Women's Health Concern estimates it to be arou=
nd 80%.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>71<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is the most comm=
on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_disorder" title=3D"Me=
nstrual disorder">menstrual disorder</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_A=
COG2015_66-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2015-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>66<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Typically, it =
starts within a year of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menarc=
he" title=3D"Menarche">first menstrual period</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysme=
norrhea_AFP2014_67-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dysmenorrhea_AFP2014-67"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>67<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When t=
here is no underlying cause, often the pain improves with age or following =
having a child.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Dysmenorrhea_ACOG2015_66-4" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Dys=
menorrhea_ACOG2015-66"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>66<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></div></div>
