<p>Menstrual products (also called "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Feminine_hygiene" title=3D"Feminine hygiene">feminine hygiene</a>" produc=
ts) are made to absorb or catch menstrual blood. A number of different prod=
ucts are available =E2=80=93 some are disposable, some are reusable. Where =
women can afford it, items used to absorb or catch menses are usually comme=
rcially manufactured products. Menstruating women manage menstruation prima=
rily by wearing menstrual products such as tampons, napkins or menstrual cu=
ps to catch the menstrual blood.
</p><p>The main disposable products (commercially manufactured) include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sanitary_napkin" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Sanitary napkin">Sanitary napkins</a> (also called sa=
nitary towels or pads) =E2=80=93 Rectangular pieces of material worn attach=
ed to the underwear to absorb menstrual flow, often with an adhesive backin=
g to hold the pad in place. Disposable pads may contain <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wood_pulp" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wood pulp">=
wood pulp</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gel" title=3D"Gel=
">gel</a> products, usually with a plastic lining and bleached.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tampon" title=3D"Tampon">Tampo=
ns</a> =E2=80=93 Disposable cylinders of treated <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Rayon" title=3D"Rayon">rayon</a>/cotton blends or all-cotton=
 fleece, usually bleached, that are inserted into the vagina to absorb mens=
trual flow.</li></ul>
<p>The main reusable products include:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_cup" title=3D"Me=
nstrual cup">Menstrual cups</a> =E2=80=93 A firm, flexible bell-shaped devi=
ce worn inside the vagina to collect menstrual flow.</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cloth_menstrual_pad" title=3D"=
Cloth menstrual pad">Reusable cloth pads</a> =E2=80=93 Pads that are made o=
f cotton (often <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organic_farming" t=
itle=3D"Organic farming">organic</a>), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Terrycloth" title=3D"Terrycloth">terrycloth</a>, or <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flannel" title=3D"Flannel">flannel</a>, and may be h=
andsewn (from material or reused old clothes and towels) or store-bought.</=
li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Period_underwear" title=3D"Per=
iod underwear">Padded panties or period-proof underwear</a> =E2=80=93 Reusa=
ble cloth (usually cotton) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Underga=
rment" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Undergarment">underwear</a> with extr=
a absorbent layers sewn in to absorb flow.</li></ul>
<p>Due to poverty, some women cannot afford commercial feminine hygiene pro=
ducts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kaur_2018_72-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Kaur_2018-72"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-73" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-73"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
73<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Instead, they use materia=
ls found in the environment or other improvised materials.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-74" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstru=
ation#cite_note-74"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>74<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-75" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-75"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>75<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Period_poverty" title=3D"Per=
iod poverty">Period poverty</a>" is a global issue affecting women and girl=
s who do not have access to safe, hygienic sanitary products.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-76" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mens=
truation#cite_note-76"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>76<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In addition, solid waste disposal syst=
ems in developing countries are often lacking, which means women have no pr=
oper place to dispose used products, such as pads.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-77" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#ci=
te_note-77"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>77<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> Inappropriate disposal of used materials also creat=
es pressures on sanitation systems as menstrual hygiene products can create=
 blockages of toilets, pipes and sewers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kaur_2018_72-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#=
cite_note-Kaur_2018-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the UK research has shown that for =
women who are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Allotment_(gardening=
)" title=3D"Allotment (gardening)">allotment</a> growers, access to sanitat=
ion for menstrual hygiene management is limited.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-78" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite=
_note-78"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>78<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Menstrual_suppression">Mens=
trual suppression</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_suppressio=
n" title=3D"Menstrual suppression">Menstrual suppression</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Due_to_hormonal_contracepti=
on">Due to hormonal contraception</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hormonal_contracepti=
on" title=3D"Hormonal contraception">Hormonal contraception</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pillpacketopen.jpg" class=3D"=
mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/com=
mons/f/f5/Pillpacketopen.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"240" height=3D"17=
0" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"240" data-file-height=3D"17=
0"></a><figcaption>Half-used blister pack of a combined oral contraceptive.=
 The white pills are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Placebos" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Placebos">placebos</a>, mainly for the purpose =
of reminding the woman to continue taking the pills.</figcaption></figure>
<p>Menstruation can be delayed by the use of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Progesterone" title=3D"Progesterone">progesterone</a> or <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Progestin" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Progestin">progestins</a>. For this purpose, oral administration of proges=
terone or progestin during cycle day 20 has been found to effectively delay=
 menstruation for at least 20 days, with menstruation starting after 2=E2=
=80=933 days have passed since discontinuing the regimen.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-Goldstuck2011_79-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Goldstuck2011-79"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hormonal_contraception" tit=
le=3D"Hormonal contraception">Hormonal contraception</a> affects the freque=
ncy, duration, severity, volume, and regularity of menstruation and menstru=
al symptoms. The most common form of hormonal contraception is the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combined_oral_contraceptive_pill" title=
=3D"Combined oral contraceptive pill">combined birth control pill</a>, whic=
h contains both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Estrogen" title=3D=
"Estrogen">estrogen</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proges=
togen" title=3D"Progestogen">progestogen</a>. Although the primary function=
 of the pill is to prevent pregnancy, it may be used to improve <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combined_oral_contraceptive_pill#Non-contrace=
ptive_use" title=3D"Combined oral contraceptive pill">some menstrual sympto=
ms and syndromes which affect menstruation</a>, such as <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polycystic_ovary_syndrome" title=3D"Polycystic ovary =
syndrome">polycystic ovary syndrome</a> (PCOS), <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Endometriosis" title=3D"Endometriosis">endometriosis</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adenomyosis" title=3D"Adenomyosis">ad=
enomyosis</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amenorrhea" title=
=3D"Amenorrhea">amenorrhea</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dy=
smenorrhea" title=3D"Dysmenorrhea">menstrual cramps</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_migraine" title=3D"Menstrual migraine">men=
strual migraines</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heavy_menstr=
ual_bleeding" title=3D"Heavy menstrual bleeding">menorrhagia</a> (excessive=
 menstrual bleeding), menstruation-related or fibroid-related anemia and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dysmenorrhea" title=3D"Dysmenorrhea"=
>dysmenorrhea</a> (painful menstruation) by creating regularity in menstrua=
l cycles and reducing overall menstrual flow.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_n=
ote-80"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-auto_81-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-auto-81"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup>
</p><p>Using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combined_oral_con=
traceptive_pill" title=3D"Combined oral contraceptive pill">combined birth =
control pill</a>, it is also possible for a woman to delay or eliminate men=
strual periods, a practice called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Menstrual_suppression" title=3D"Menstrual suppression">menstrual suppressio=
n</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-82" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-82"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some women do this s=
imply for convenience in the short-term,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-83=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> while others prefer to eliminate periods altogether when poss=
ible. This can be done either by skipping the placebo pills, or using an <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extended_cycle_combined_oral_contrac=
eptive_pill" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Extended cycle combined oral co=
ntraceptive pill">extended cycle combined oral contraceptive pill</a>, whic=
h were first marketed in the U.S. in the early 2000s. This continuous admin=
istration of active pills without the placebo can lead to the achievement o=
f amenorrhea in 80% of users within 1 year of use.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:4_84=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruati=
on#cite_note-:4-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>84<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Due_to_breastfeeding">Due t=
o breastfeeding</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lactational_amenorrh=
ea" title=3D"Lactational amenorrhea">Lactational amenorrhea</a></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breastfeeding" title=3D"Breastf=
eeding">Breastfeeding</a> causes negative feedback to occur on pulse secret=
ion of gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-85" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-85"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>85=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Depending on the strength o=
f the negative feedback, breastfeeding women may experience complete suppre=
ssion of follicular development, follicular development but no ovulation, o=
r normal menstrual cycles may resume.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-mcneilly_86-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite=
_note-mcneilly-86"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>86<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Suppression of ovulation is more likely when=
 suckling occurs more frequently.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-autogenerated1_87-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#ci=
te_note-autogenerated1-87"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>87<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The production of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prolactin" title=3D"Prolactin">prolactin</a> in resp=
onse to suckling is important to maintaining lactational amenorrhea.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-88" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Menstruation#cite_note-88"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>88<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> On average, women who are fully b=
reastfeeding whose infants suckle frequently experience a return of menstru=
ation at fourteen and a half months postpartum. There is a wide range of re=
sponse among individual breastfeeding women, however, with some experiencin=
g return of menstruation at two months and others remaining amenorrheic for=
 up to 42 months postpartum.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-89" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-89"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>89<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Society_and_culture">Societ=
y and culture</h2></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Culture_and_menstrua=
tion" title=3D"Culture and menstruation">Culture and menstruation</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Amra_Padatik_India.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9=
/96/Amra_Padatik_India.jpg/250px-Amra_Padatik_India.jpg" decoding=3D"async"=
 width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"=
3648" data-file-height=3D"2736"></a><figcaption>Amra Padatik India, celebra=
tion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrual_Hygiene_Day" tit=
le=3D"Menstrual Hygiene Day">Menstrual Hygiene Day</a> in India</figcaption=
></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Etymology_and_terminology">=
Etymology and terminology</h3></div>
<p>The word <i>menstruation</i> is etymologically related to <i><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moon" title=3D"Moon">moon</a></i>. The terms =
<i>menstruation</i> and <i>menses</i> are derived from the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin" title=3D"Latin">Latin</a> <span title=3D"La=
tin-language text"><i lang=3D"la">mensis</i></span> <span class=3D"gloss-qu=
ot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss-text">month</span><span class=3D"gloss-quo=
t">'</span>, which in turn relates to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Ancient_Greek" title=3D"Ancient Greek">ancient Greek</a> <span titl=
e=3D"Ancient Greek (to 1453)-language romanization"><i lang=3D"grc-Latn">me=
ne</i></span> <span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span><span class=3D"gloss-text"=
>moon</span><span class=3D"gloss-quot">'</span> and to the roots of the Eng=
lish words <i>month</i> and <i>moon</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Allen,_Kevin_20=
07_239_90-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
enstruation#cite_note-Allen,_Kevin_2007_239-90"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>90<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Some organizations have begun to use the term "menstruator" instead =
of "menstruating women", a term that has been in use since at least 2010.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-chapter_68_91-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-chapter_68-91"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>91<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <i>M=
enstruator</i> is used by activists and scholars in order to "express solid=
arity with women who do not menstruate, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Transgender_men" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Transgender men">tran=
sgender men</a> who do, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inters=
ex" title=3D"Intersex">intersexual</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Genderqueer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Genderqueer">genderque=
er</a> individuals".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-chapter_68_91-1" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-chapter_6=
8-91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>91<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / loca=
tion: 950">:=E2=80=8A950=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The term can be contentious =
between different schools of feminist thought; however, the argument is mad=
e that since gender identities are lived, the reality is that people of dif=
ferent genders menstruate.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-chapter_68_91-2" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-cha=
pter_68-91"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>91<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page =
/ location: 950">:=E2=80=8A950=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The term "people who m=
enstruate" is also used.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-92" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-92"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>92<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Traditions,_taboos_and_educ=
ation"><span id=3D"Traditions.2C_taboos_and_education"></span>Traditions, t=
aboos and education</h3></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation_in_Islam" t=
itle=3D"Menstruation in Islam">Menstruation in Islam</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woman_prayer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Woman =
prayer">Woman prayer</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isti=
hadha" title=3D"Istihadha">Istihadha</a></div>
<p>Many religions have menstruation-related traditions, for example: Islam =
prohibits sexual contact with women during menstruation in the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2nd_chapter_of_the_Quran" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"2nd chapter of the Quran">2nd chapter of the Quran</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Quran_93-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Quran-93"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>93<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Some scholars argue=
 that menstruating women are in a state in which they are unable to maintai=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wudhu" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Wudhu">wudhu</a>, and are therefore prohibited from touching the Arab=
ic version of the Qur'an.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ahadith_94-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-ahadith=
-94"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>94<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Judaism" title=
=3D"Judaism">Judaism</a>, a woman during menstruation is called <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niddah" title=3D"Niddah">Niddah</a> and may b=
e banned from certain actions. For example, the Jewish <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torah" title=3D"Torah">Torah</a> prohibits sexual inte=
rcourse with a menstruating woman.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-95" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-95"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>95<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hinduism" title=3D"Hind=
uism">Hinduism</a>, menstruating women are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Culture_and_menstruation#Hinduism" title=3D"Culture and menstruati=
on">traditionally considered ritually impure</a> and given rules to follow.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-96" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-96"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9=
6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-97" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite=
_note-97"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>97<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> In Zoroastrianism, if a woman's menses did not stop a=
fter nine days, it was considered the work of the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Daeva" title=3D"Daeva">da=C4=93vas</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
98" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruati=
on#cite_note-98"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>98<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Menstruation education is frequently taught in combination with sex =
education at school in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_wor=
ld" title=3D"Western world">Western countries</a>, although girls may prefe=
r their mothers to be the primary source of information about menstruation =
and puberty.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sooki_99-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Sooki-99"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>99<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Information about menstruation is often shared among friends and peers, wh=
ich may promote a more positive outlook on puberty.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-100"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#=
cite_note-100"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>100<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> The quality of menstrual education in a society=
 determines the accuracy of people's understanding of the process.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Allen_2011_101-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Allen_2011-101"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>101<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In man=
y Western countries where menstruation is a taboo subject, girls tend to co=
nceal the fact that they may be menstruating and struggle to ensure that th=
ey give no sign of menstruation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Allen_2011_101-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_n=
ote-Allen_2011-101"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>101<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Effective educational programs are essenti=
al to providing children and adolescents with clear and accurate informatio=
n about menstruation. Schools can be an appropriate place for menstrual edu=
cation to take place.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kirby_2002_102-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Kirby_2=
002-102"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> Programs led by peers or third-party agencies are ano=
ther option.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kirby_2002_102-1" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Kirby_2002-102">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>102<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup> Low-income girls are less likely to receive proper sex educati=
on on puberty, leading to a decreased understanding of why menstruation occ=
urs and the associated physiological changes that take place. This has been=
 shown to cause the development of a negative attitude towards menstruation=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-103" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-103"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>103<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Seclusion_during_menstruati=
on">Seclusion during menstruation</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chhaupadi" ti=
tle=3D"Chhaupadi">Chhaupadi</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Seclusion_of_girls_at_puberty" title=3D"Seclusion of girls at puberty">Se=
clusion of girls at puberty</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mass-Community_Health_Teaching=
.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.or=
g/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/62/Mass-Community_Health_Teaching.JPG/250px-Mas=
s-Community_Health_Teaching.JPG" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D=
"167" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"5184" data-file-height=
=3D"3456"></a><figcaption>Awareness raising through education is taking pla=
ce among women and girls to modify or eliminate the practice of <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chhaupadi" title=3D"Chhaupadi">chhaupadi</a> =
in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nepal" title=3D"Nepal">Nepal</a=
>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>In some cultures, women were isolated during menstruation due to menstru=
al <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taboo" title=3D"Taboo">taboos</=
a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Gottlieb2020_104-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Gottlieb2020-104"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>104<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> This is because they are seen as unclean, dangerous, or bringing ba=
d luck to those who encounter them. These practices are common in parts of =
South Asia including India.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-KleinmanGood1985_105-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_=
note-KleinmanGood1985-105"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>105<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A 1983 report found women refrainin=
g  from household chore during this period in India.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Del=
aneyLupton1988_106-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-DelaneyLupton1988-106"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>106<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chhaupadi" title=3D"Chhaupadi">Chhaupadi<=
/a> is a social practice that occurs in the western part of Nepal for <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindu" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"H=
indu">Hindu</a> women, which prohibits a woman from participating in everyd=
ay activities during menstruation. Women are considered <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Impurity" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Impurity">im=
pure</a> during this time and are kept out of the house and have to live in=
 a shed. Although chhaupadi was outlawed by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Supreme_Court_of_Nepal" title=3D"Supreme Court of Nepal">Supr=
eme Court of Nepal</a> in 2005, the tradition is slow to change.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-107" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Menstruation#cite_note-107"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>107<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-108" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-1=
08"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>108<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> Women and girls in cultures which practice such seclusion =
are often confined to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation=
_hut" title=3D"Menstruation hut">menstruation huts</a>, which are places of=
 isolation used by cultures with strong menstrual <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Taboo" title=3D"Taboo">taboos</a>. The practice has recentl=
y come under fire due to related fatalities. Nepal criminalized the practic=
e in 2017 after deaths were reported after the elongated isolation periods,=
 but "the practice of isolating menstruating women and girls continues."<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-FAWCO_2019_109-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-FAWCO_2019-109"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>109<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> No=
t all cultures villainize menstruation, the Beng people of West Africa cons=
ider menstrual blood as sacred and recognize its significance in reproducti=
on.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-110" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-110"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>110<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Beliefs_around_synchrony">B=
eliefs around synchrony</h3></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Effects_of_the_moon">Effect=
s of the moon</h4></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lunar_effect" title=3D"L=
unar effect">Lunar effect</a></div>
<p>Even though the average length of the human <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Menstrual_cycle" title=3D"Menstrual cycle">menstrual cycle</a>=
 is similar to that of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lunar_c=
ycle" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lunar cycle">lunar cycle</a>, in moder=
n humans there is no relation between the two.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-111" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_=
note-111"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>111<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> The relationship is believed to be a coincidence.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-112" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-112"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11=
2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-113" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cit=
e_note-113"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>113<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> Light exposure does not appear to affect the menst=
rual cycle in humans.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Kris2013_114-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Kris2013-=
114"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>114<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup> A meta-analysis of studies from 1996 showed no correlatio=
n between the human menstrual cycle and the lunar cycle,<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-115" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstrua=
tion#cite_note-115"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>115<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> nor did data analyzed by period-tracking a=
pp Clue, submitted by 1.5<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>million women,=
 of 7.5<span class=3D"nowrap">&nbsp;</span>million menstrual cycles; howeve=
r, the lunar cycle and the average menstrual cycle were found to be basical=
ly equal in length.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Clue_116-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Clue-116"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>116<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Cohabitation">Cohabitation<=
/h4></div>
<p>Beginning in 1971, some research suggested that menstrual cycles of coha=
biting women became synchronized (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Menstrual_synchrony" title=3D"Menstrual synchrony">menstrual synchrony</a>)=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Mclintock_117-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Mclintock-117"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>117<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> Subsequent research has called this hypothesis into question.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-118" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M=
enstruation#cite_note-118"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>118<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A 2013 review concluded that menstr=
ual synchrony likely does not exist.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Harris2013_119-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#ci=
te_note-Harris2013-119"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>119<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Work">Work</h3></div>
<p>Some countries, mainly in Asia, have <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Menstrual_leave" title=3D"Menstrual leave">menstrual leave</a> to pro=
vide women with either paid or unpaid leave of absence from their employmen=
t while they are menstruating.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Matchar_2014_120-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_n=
ote-Matchar_2014-120"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>120<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Countries with policies include Japan,=
 Taiwan, Indonesia, and South Korea.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Levitt_2020_121-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#c=
ite_note-Levitt_2020-121"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>121<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-King2021_122-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#ci=
te_note-King2021-122"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>122<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The practice is controversial due to c=
oncerns that it bolsters the perception of women as weak, inefficient worke=
rs,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Matchar_2014_120-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-Matchar_2014-120"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>120<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> as well as concerns that it is unfair to men,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12=
3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruatio=
n#cite_note-123"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>123<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-124" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Menstruation#cite_note-124"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>124<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> and that it furthers gender stereotypes and the medicalization of men=
struation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Levitt_2020_121-1" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
